`IFormFile` buffers the entire body into memory by default. For large uploads, bypass model binding and read the multipart stream directly.

**1. Disable request size limits**

```csharp
// Program.cs
builder.WebApplication.MapPost("/upload", HandleUpload)
    .DisableAntiforgery()
    .WithMetadata(new RequestSizeLimitAttribute(2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024)); // 2 GB

// Also in Kestrel config:
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024);
```

**2. Stream multipart sections to disk**

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.WebUtilities;
using Microsoft.Net.Http.Headers;

async Task<IResult> HandleUpload(HttpRequest request)
{
    if (!request.HasFormContentType ||
        !MediaTypeHeaderValue.TryParse(request.ContentType, out var mt))
        return Results.BadRequest("Expected multipart/form-data");

    var boundary = HeaderUtilities.RemoveQuotes(mt.Boundary).Value;
    var reader = new MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);

    MultipartSection? section;
    while ((section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync()) is not null)
    {
        if (!ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(
                section.ContentDisposition, out var cd) ||
            !cd.IsFileDisposition())
            continue;

        var trustedName = Path.GetRandomFileName();          // never trust the client name
        var savePath = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads", trustedName);

        await using var fs = new FileStream(
            savePath, FileMode.Create, FileAccess.Write,
            FileShare.None, bufferSize: 81920, useAsync: true);

        await section.Body.CopyToAsync(fs);                  // streams ~80 KB at a time
    }

    return Results.Ok("Upload complete");
}
```

**Why this works:** `MultipartReader` reads each section as a forward-only stream — only the `bufferSize` (80 KB here) is ever in memory, regardless of file size.

**Key pitfalls to avoid:**
- **Don't use `Request.Form`** — it buffers everything like `IFormFile`.
- **Set `bufferSize` on `FileStream`** — the default 4 KB causes excessive I/O syscalls at 2 GB.
- **Kestrel + reverse proxy** — if behind Nginx/IIS, raise `client_max_body_size` / `maxAllowedContentLength` there too.
